sentences: Jabo Williams (c. 1895 – 1953 or 1954) was an American boogie-woogie and blues pianist and songwriter.
His total recorded output was a mere eight sides, which included his two best-known "stunningly primitive" songs, "Pratt City Blues" and "Jab's Blues" (1932).
He may have been named Jimmie Williams and may have been born around 1895.
In May 1932, Williams recorded eight tracks in a recording studio in Grafton, Wisconsin, for  Paramount.
The timing was not fortuitous, as Paramount stopped recording that year and went out of business in 1935.
